1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3 Bc5 6. Nb3 Be7 {A very
interesting variation which I've begun playing recently. The main expert of
this system was grandmaster Vladimir Epishin, although recently he seems to
have abandoned it.} 7. Be3 $5 {Recently players have begun to tackle this line
in many different ways apart from the classical approach; this is one such way,
which despite its odd appearence can be rather dangerous.} Nf6 8. N1d2 Nc6 {
Keeping flexibility and limiting White's options, as I might play ...d5
immediately in some cases. Of course my knight should be placed on c6 rather
than d7 here, as ...Nb4 is always an important option and I will want to
retreat to d7 with my other knight after g4-g5.  Technically this is a novelty
but play transposes to normal lines in one move.} 9. f4 d6 ({I wasn't
completely satisfied with} 9... e5 10. f5 d5 11. Qf3 {, since White maintains
his stronghold on f5, which practically guarantuees success in attack if I
ever castle, while my light-squared bishop is very limited. However, it should
be mentioned that in Delgado Ramirez-Nogueiras, Santa Clara 2007 Black went
for this position with a tempo less, after 10...e5 11.f5 d5 (instead of 10...
o-o as I played), so perhaps this is an option to be investigated.}) 10. Qf3 {
A fundamental decision for White is where to place his queen and whether or
not to stop ...Nb4 with c3. My opponent's play seems most logical to me, but
in the game he encountered serious problems so perhaps White should prefer to
play with 10.c3!?.} O-O 11. O-O-O {Black has some problems to solve here.
White's setup is clever in that Black cannot easily make contact with it,
meanwhile he is ready to advance quickly and dangerously on the kingside with
g4-g5; usually White isn't able achieve such a rapid attack. For instance, a
natural move such as 11...b5 does nothing to challenge White and he can calmly
advance with 12.g4 Bb7 13.g5 Nd7 14.h4, when I fail to see what Black plays
next.  More sensible is 11...Nb4, taking advantage of White's piece placement
and removing the valuable light-squared bishop. Then we reach a structure 
(which can also be seen in Caruana-Van der Wiel, Wijk aan Zee 2008) where
Black is solid and has the bishop pair, but White dominates in the centre and
has a clear plan of attack on the kingside, while Black desperately lacks
meaningful counterplay. However, that isn't the end of the story: after 11...
Nb4 12.Kb1 Nxd3 13.cxd3 Black can quickly generate threats with 13...a5!?,
when White has problems with his awkward knight on b3. It would like to go to
d4 but that will always be met with ...e5. White should therefore play the
prophylactic 14.g4! a4 15.Nd4 a3 16.b3 (this is no great achievement for Black)
, when 16...e5 is met by 17.Nf5 and White retains the upper hand. If Black
doesn't take extreme measures such as 13...a5 he can easily end up getting
slaughtered on the kingside. See for instance the game Colovic-Ivanov,J where
Black played superficially (later on his play transcended from superficial to
suicidal with the manouver ...Kg8-f7-e8) with 13...b5 and got crushed on the
kingside.      So perhaps I shouldn't have committed my king with 10...o-o?
Has my play been too slow here and am I already worse? In fact, with very
attentive play I can solve all my problems and even put pressure on White. My
next move looks somewhat outrageous but is in fact a purely positional way to
fight against White's concept.} a5 $1 {The same idea as in the 11...Nb4
variation, but crucially inverting the move order! Now the knight will not be
able to move to d4 after ...a4 as Black will win an exchange with ...Nxd4 Bxd4
e5 and ...Bg4. And if White plays 12.Kb1 a4 13.Nc1 Black reverts to the
original idea with 13...a3 14.b3 Nb4, when the knight is grossly misplaced on
c1. However, White can also play aggressively with 12.Nc4 and I had to see how
to counter his activity.    Of course I was very proud to have seen this idea.}
(11... b5 12. g4 Bb7 13. g5 Nd7 14. h4 $36) (11... Nb4 12. Kb1 Nxd3 13. cxd3 a5
(13... b5 $6 14. g4 e5 15. f5 Nd7 16. h4 f6 17. Rdg1 Kf7 $2 18. g5 Rh8 19. Qg3
Bf8 20. h5 Ke8 21. Nf3 Qe7 22. Rc1 a5 23. Nxa5 Nc5 24. Nc6 Qf7 25. Nb4 Ra4 26.
Nd5 {1-0 Colovic-Ivanov, Campillos 2007}) 14. g4 $1 a4 (14... e5 15. f5 a4 16.
Nc1 a3 17. b3 {with good attacking chances on the kingside, although I'm fully
aware the machine doesn't agree with my assessment}) 15. Nd4 a3 16. b3 e5 17.
Nf5 Bxf5 18. gxf5 Nd7 19. d4 exd4 20. Bxd4 Bf6 21. Nc4 $16) 12. Nc4 {This is
the most challenging move. But despite the impressive appearence White's
pieces are quite loose and liable to be harrassed with some timely thrusts (...
e5, ...d5, ...b5 or ...a3, and of course the typical ...Nb4). Black's position
only looks passive; in fact my pieces possess enormous latent energy.} (12. a3
a4 13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 e5 15. fxe5 dxe5 16. Bxe5 Bg4 17. Qg3 Bxd1 18. Rxd1
Qb6 19. Nc4 Qe6 $15) (12. Kb1 a4 13. Nc1 a3 14. b3 Nb4 {is not entirely clear
but looks quite nice for Black, since White is passively placed.}) (12. Qg3 a4
13. Nd4 Nb4 14. Kb1 a3 15. b3 Nxd3 16. cxd3 e5 $1 17. fxe5 (17. Nf5 Bxf5 18.
exf5 Nd5 $17) (17. Ne2 Bg4) 17... Nh5 18. Qf3 dxe5 19. Qxh5 exd4 20. Bf4 Be6
$17) 12... a4 13. Bb6 {Tempting but not very strong. My queen is better placed
on e8 than d8 in case the centre opens (and it almost certainly will), while
White needed b6 for his knight. Besides this there were two knight retreats.} (
13. Nbd2 Nb4 14. Kb1 Nxd3 15. cxd3 d5 16. Nb6 Ra6 17. Nxc8 Qxc8 18. Rc1 Rc6 $15
) (13. Nd4 $142 a3 $1 14. b3 (14. Nxa3 $1 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 e5 16. fxe5 dxe5 17.
Bxe5 Bg4 18. Qg3 Bxd1 19. Rxd1 Qc8 {is an interesting try for White, with very
unclear play}) 14... Nb4 15. Kb1 d5 $36) 13... Qe8 14. Nbd2 {Weaker is 14.Nd4 
(we have already seen the idea of ...a3 in reply to Nd4, and in this case it
is even stronger) so this is nearly forced. White is very much on the
defensive at this point.} (14. Nd4 a3 $1 15. Nxa3 (15. b3 e5 16. Nxc6 Qxc6 17.
fxe5 dxe5 18. Qg3 Be6 $19) 15... Nxd4 16. Bxd4 e5 17. fxe5 dxe5 18. Bb5 (18.
Bxe5 Bg4 19. Qg3 Bxd1 20. Rxd1 Nh5 21. Qg4 Bxa3 22. Qxh5 Ra5 $19) 18... Rxa3
19. Qxa3 Bxa3 20. Bxe8 Bd6 21. Bxf7+ Kxf7 22. Bc3 Bc7 $17) 14... d5 15. Ne5 a3
16. b3 Nb4 17. Kb1 dxe4 18. Nxe4 $2 {My opponent clearly had overlooked 20...
e5!. Instead 18.Bxe4 limits the damage, although Black still keeps a pleasant
advantage.} (18. Bxe4 Nbd5 19. Bd4 Nxe4 20. Nxe4 f6 21. Nc4 Qc6 $15) 18... Nfd5
19. Bd4 f6 20. Nc4 e5 $1 $17 {Despite the very shaky appearence of Black's
position, the position is almost hopeless for White. He is simply losing a
pawn.    However, at this point I was low on time and under such circumstances
it can be easy to "see ghosts". I resolved to play this quickly before I
changed my mind.} 21. Ned6 (21. fxe5 fxe5) (21. Be3 f5 22. Ned6 e4 23. Nxe8
exf3 $19) (21. Ba1 Nxd3 22. Ned6 Qc6 23. Rxd3 Nxf4 24. Qxc6 bxc6 25. Nxc8 Raxc8
26. Rd2 Nd5 {gave White minimal chances to defend.}) 21... Bxd6 {Perhaps 21...
Qc6 is stronger, but this reduces the number of lines to calculate. It will
also be useful to have ...Qxc2 as a counterattacking option in case the
light-squared bishop is removed.} 22. Nxd6 Qc6 23. Nxc8 $2 (23. fxe5 fxe5 24.
Bxh7+ (24. Qe4 Nxd3 25. Rxd3 exd4) 24... Kxh7 25. Qxf8 Qxc2+ 26. Ka1 Qxa2#) (
23. Bc4 exd4 (23... Qxd6 $2 24. Bc3) 24. Nxc8 Raxc8 25. Rxd4 Kh8 26. Rxd5 Nxd5
27. Qxd5 Qc7 $19) ({The best chance was} 23. Ba1 $1 {, as I pointed out to my
opponent after the game. White will limit his material losses, but with an
extra pawn and good play against White's weak king Black should win:} Qxd6 (
23... Nxd3 $143 $6 24. Rxd3 Nxf4 25. Qxc6 bxc6 26. Rd2 Be6 27. g3 Nd5 28. c4
Ne3 29. Re1 Nf5 30. Nxf5 Bxf5+ 31. Kc1 $15) 24. Be4 Be6 25. c4 exf4 26. cxd5 (
26. Qh5 f5 27. cxd5 fxe4 28. dxe6 Qxe6 29. Qg5 Qg6 30. Qxg6 hxg6 31. Rd7 Rf7
32. Rd4 Nd3 $19) 26... Bd7 $17) 23... Raxc8 24. Bc4 exd4 $2 {With little time
I saw a clear path to a winning position and took it, but in fact I could have
forced immediate resignation with 24...b5.} (24... b5 $1 25. Bxd5+ Nxd5 26. c4
bxc4 27. Bxe5 Rfd8 $19) 25. Rxd4 Kh8 26. Rxd5 (26. c3 Nxc3+ 27. Qxc3 Qxg2 $19)
(26. Rhd1 b5 27. Rxd5 Nxd5) 26... Nxd5 27. Qxd5 Qc7 {The position is
absolutely hopeless for White, as apart from his material losses White will
have to deal with the mating threats around his king.} 28. Rf1 Rcd8 29. Qf5 Rd4
{For the second time I missed an immediate win with ...b5, but of course my
move is good enough.} (29... b5 $142 $1 30. Qxb5 (30. Bd3 g6 31. Qxb5 Qc3)
30... Qxf4 $19) 30. g3 b5 $1 $19 31. Qxb5 (31. Bxb5 Qc3) (31. Bd3 g6 32. Qxb5
Qc3 33. Kc1 Qa1+ 34. Kd2 Qxf1 $19) 31... Rb8 32. Re1 Qd8 33. Kc1 {This cheeky
move made a funny impression on me. But of course it changes nothing.} Rxb5 34.
Bxb5 Rd7 0-1

